\begin{center}\rule{0.5\linewidth}{0.5pt}\end{center}

\section{Methods}\label{methods}

\subsection{3.1 System Overview}\label{system-overview}

We present a privacy-preserving phenotype matching framework that
enables federated rare disease patient discovery while protecting
sensitive clinical information. Our system integrates three
complementary privacy mechanisms---Private Set Intersection (PSI),
differential privacy (DP), and k-anonymity---within a modular
architecture compatible with established genomic data sharing standards.

The framework operates on patient records encoded as GA4GH Phenopackets
(Jacobsen et al., 2022), with phenotypes represented using Human
Phenotype Ontology (HPO) terms (Köhler et al., 2021). Given a query
patient \emph{Q} and a database of \emph{n} patients \emph{D = \{P₁, P₂,
\ldots, Pₙ\}}, the system computes privacy-preserving similarity scores
\emph{s(Q, Pᵢ)} and returns the top-\emph{k} most similar patients
without revealing the precise phenotype overlap or non-matching terms.

Figure 1 illustrates the system architecture. A query phenopacket first
undergoes rare term filtering to remove quasi-identifying phenotypes.
The filtered query then enters the PSI protocol, which computes set
intersection cardinality without revealing individual terms.
Differential privacy noise is added to similarity scores, and finally,
k-anonymity checks suppress results from insufficiently sized cohorts.

\subsection{3.2 Data Representation}\label{data-representation}

\subsubsection{3.2.1 GA4GH Phenopackets}\label{ga4gh-phenopackets-1}

We adopt the Global Alliance for Genomics and Health (GA4GH) Phenopacket
schema version 2.0 as our primary data representation (Jacobsen et al.,
2022). Phenopackets provide a standardized, computable representation of
clinical phenotype data that facilitates interoperability across
institutions and computational systems.

Each phenopacket \emph{P} contains:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Subject}: Patient identifier and demographic information (sex,
  age at encounter)
\item
  \textbf{Phenotypic Features}: A set of observed clinical phenotypes
  \emph{Φ(P) = \{φ₁, φ₂, \ldots, φₘ\}}, where each \emph{φᵢ} is an HPO
  term
\item
  \textbf{Diseases}: Diagnosed conditions with ontology identifiers
  (OMIM, Orphanet)
\item
  \textbf{Metadata}: Provenance information including creation timestamp
  and contributing resources
\end{itemize}

Formally, we represent a patient's phenotype profile as the set of HPO
term identifiers:

\[\Phi(P) = \{t \in \mathcal{H} : t \text{ is observed in } P\}\]

where \(\mathcal{H}\) denotes the set of all HPO terms.

\subsubsection{3.2.2 Human Phenotype
Ontology}\label{human-phenotype-ontology}

The Human Phenotype Ontology (HPO) provides a standardized vocabulary of
18,000+ phenotypic abnormality terms organized as a directed acyclic
graph (DAG) (Köhler et al., 2021). Each term \emph{t ∈ H} has:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  A unique identifier (e.g., HP:0001250 for ``Seizure'')
\item
  A human-readable label and definition
\item
  Hierarchical relationships to parent (more general) and child (more
  specific) terms
\end{itemize}

We denote the ancestor set of term \emph{t} as \emph{Anc(t)} and the
descendant set as \emph{Desc(t)}. The root term HP:0000001 (``All'') is
an ancestor of every term in the ontology.

The ontology structure enables semantic similarity computation and
supports privacy-preserving generalization, where specific terms can be
replaced with more general parent terms to reduce identifiability.

\subsubsection{3.2.3 Information Content}\label{information-content}

Information content (IC) quantifies the specificity of an HPO term based
on its frequency in a reference corpus (Resnik, 1995). We compute IC
using two approaches:

\textbf{Corpus-based IC.} Given a corpus of phenopackets \emph{C}, the
probability of observing term \emph{t} is:

\[P(t) = \frac{|\{P \in C : t \in \Phi(P) \lor \exists t' \in \Phi(P) : t \in Anc(t')\}|}{|C|}\]

The information content is then:

\[IC(t) = -\log_2 P(t)\]

Terms with lower corpus frequency have higher IC, indicating greater
diagnostic specificity. For example, ``Seizure'' (HP:0001250) appearing
in 2,530 of 12,974 diseases has lower IC than ``Myoclonic seizure''
(HP:0002123) appearing in 412 diseases.

\textbf{Intrinsic IC.} When corpus statistics are unavailable, we
estimate IC from ontology structure using descendant counts (Sánchez et
al., 2011):

\[IC_{intrinsic}(t) = 1 - \frac{\log(|Desc(t)| + 1)}{\log(|\mathcal{H}|)}\]

Leaf terms with no descendants receive maximum IC, while the root
receives IC = 0.

\subsection{3.3 Phenotype Similarity
Metrics}\label{phenotype-similarity-metrics}

We implement four similarity metrics spanning set-theoretic,
vector-space, and semantic approaches. All metrics produce scores in
{[}0, 1{]}, where 1 indicates identical phenotype profiles.

\subsubsection{3.3.1 Jaccard Similarity}\label{jaccard-similarity}

The Jaccard index measures phenotype overlap as the ratio of
intersection to union cardinality:

\[J(\Phi(Q), \Phi(P)) = \frac{|\Phi(Q) \cap \Phi(P)|}{|\Phi(Q) \cup \Phi(P)|}\]

Jaccard similarity treats all HPO terms as equally informative and
requires exact term matches. While computationally efficient, it does
not account for semantic relationships between related terms.

\subsubsection{3.3.2 Cosine Similarity with IC
Weighting}\label{cosine-similarity-with-ic-weighting}

Cosine similarity represents phenotype profiles as vectors in a
high-dimensional space indexed by HPO terms. We weight each dimension by
information content to emphasize rare, diagnostically specific
phenotypes:

\[\cos_{IC}(\Phi(Q), \Phi(P)) = \frac{\sum_{t \in \Phi(Q) \cap \Phi(P)} IC(t)^2}{\sqrt{\sum_{t \in \Phi(Q)} IC(t)^2} \cdot \sqrt{\sum_{t \in \Phi(P)} IC(t)^2}}\]

When IC weights are unavailable, we use uniform weighting (IC(t) = 1 for
all t), reducing to standard cosine similarity on binary term vectors.

\subsubsection{3.3.3 Resnik Similarity}\label{resnik-similarity}

Resnik similarity leverages the ontology structure to compare terms
based on their most informative common ancestor (MICA) (Resnik, 1995).
For two terms \emph{t₁} and \emph{t₂}:

\[sim_{Resnik}(t_1, t_2) = IC(MICA(t_1, t_2))\]

where:

\[MICA(t_1, t_2) = \arg\max_{t \in Anc(t_1) \cap Anc(t_2)} IC(t)\]

To extend pairwise term similarity to phenotype sets, we employ the
Best-Match Average (BMA) strategy (Pesquita et al., 2009):

\[BMA(\Phi(Q), \Phi(P)) = \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{1}{|\Phi(Q)|}\sum_{q \in \Phi(Q)} \max_{p \in \Phi(P)} sim(q, p) + \frac{1}{|\Phi(P)|}\sum_{p \in \Phi(P)} \max_{q \in \Phi(Q)} sim(p, q)\right)\]

BMA computes the average best match in both directions, ensuring
symmetric similarity scores.

\subsubsection{3.3.4 Simplified Resnik
Similarity}\label{simplified-resnik-similarity}

For computational efficiency in privacy-preserving protocols, we
implement a simplified Resnik variant that approximates semantic
similarity using only exact term matches weighted by IC:

\[sim_{simple}(\Phi(Q), \Phi(P)) = \frac{\sum_{t \in \Phi(Q) \cap \Phi(P)} IC(t)}{\max\left(\sum_{t \in \Phi(Q)} IC(t), \sum_{t \in \Phi(P)} IC(t)\right)}\]

This formulation avoids ontology traversal during similarity computation
while preserving the emphasis on rare phenotypes through IC weighting.

\subsection{3.4 Privacy-Preserving
Mechanisms}\label{privacy-preserving-mechanisms}

Our framework implements three complementary privacy mechanisms that can
be composed to provide layered protection. Each mechanism addresses
distinct privacy concerns and offers configurable parameters to balance
utility and protection.

\subsubsection{3.4.1 Private Set Intersection
(PSI)}\label{private-set-intersection-psi}

Private Set Intersection enables two parties to compute the intersection
of their sets without revealing elements outside the intersection
(Meadows, 1986). We implement Diffie-Hellman-based PSI using elliptic
curve cryptography.

\textbf{Protocol Description.} Let \emph{Q} denote the query party with
phenotype set \emph{Φ(Q)} and \emph{S} denote the server with database
phenotypes. The protocol proceeds as follows:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  \textbf{Setup}: Both parties agree on elliptic curve parameters (NIST
  P-256/secp256r1) and a hash function \emph{H: \{0,1\}} → G* mapping
  strings to curve points.
\item
  \textbf{Query Blinding}: The query party samples a random scalar
  \emph{α ← Z\_q} and computes blinded query elements:
  \[\forall t \in \Phi(Q): B_t = H(t)^\alpha\]
\item
  \textbf{Server Processing}: For each blinded element \emph{B\_t}, the
  server samples \emph{β ← Z\_q} and computes:
  \[\forall t \in \Phi(Q): C_t = B_t^\beta = H(t)^{\alpha\beta}\]

  The server also computes its own blinded elements:
  \[\forall t' \in \Phi(S): D_{t'} = H(t')^\beta\]
\item
  \textbf{Query Completion}: The query party raises server elements to
  its secret:
  \[\forall t' \in \Phi(S): E_{t'} = D_{t'}^\alpha = H(t')^{\alpha\beta}\]
\item
  \textbf{Intersection}: Elements appearing in both \emph{\{C\_t\}} and
  \emph{\{E\_\{t'\}\}} correspond to the intersection \emph{Φ(Q) ∩
  Φ(S)}.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Security Guarantees.} Under the Decisional Diffie-Hellman (DDH)
assumption, this protocol is secure in the semi-honest
(honest-but-curious) adversary model. Neither party learns elements
outside the intersection.

\textbf{Cardinality-Only Mode.} For enhanced privacy, we support a
cardinality-only variant that reveals only \textbar{}\emph{Φ(Q) ∩
Φ(S)}\textbar{} without disclosing which specific terms match. This
enables Jaccard similarity computation:

\[J = \frac{|Φ(Q) \cap Φ(S)|}{|Φ(Q)| + |Φ(S)| - |Φ(Q) \cap Φ(S)|}\]

\subsubsection{3.4.2 Differential Privacy}\label{differential-privacy-1}

Differential privacy provides a rigorous mathematical framework for
quantifying privacy loss (Dwork et al., 2006). A randomized mechanism
\emph{M} satisfies (ε, δ)-differential privacy if for all datasets
\emph{D₁}, \emph{D₂} differing in one record and all output sets
\emph{S}:

\[\Pr[M(D_1) \in S] \leq e^\varepsilon \cdot \Pr[M(D_2) \in S] + \delta\]

The privacy parameter ε (epsilon) controls the privacy-utility tradeoff,
with smaller ε providing stronger privacy but requiring more noise.

\textbf{Laplace Mechanism.} For a numeric query \emph{f} with
sensitivity \emph{Δf = max\_\{D₁,D₂\} \textbar f(D₁) - f(D₂)\textbar{}},
the Laplace mechanism achieves (ε, 0)-DP by adding noise:

\[M(D) = f(D) + Lap\left(\frac{\Delta f}{\varepsilon}\right)\]

where \emph{Lap(b)} denotes a random variable drawn from the Laplace
distribution with scale \emph{b}.

We apply the Laplace mechanism to privatize similarity scores. For
similarity functions bounded in {[}0, 1{]}, the sensitivity is Δf = 1,
yielding:

\[\tilde{s}(Q, P) = s(Q, P) + Lap\left(\frac{1}{\varepsilon}\right)\]

\textbf{Gaussian Mechanism.} For (ε, δ)-DP with δ \textgreater{} 0, the
Gaussian mechanism adds normally distributed noise:

\[M(D) = f(D) + \mathcal{N}\left(0, \sigma^2\right)\]

where:

\[\sigma = \frac{\Delta f \cdot \sqrt{2\ln(1.25/\delta)}}{\varepsilon}\]

The Gaussian mechanism often provides better utility for the same
privacy guarantee when δ is acceptably small (e.g., δ = 10⁻⁵).

\textbf{Exponential Mechanism.} For selecting among discrete options
(e.g., top-k patients), the exponential mechanism samples outputs
proportionally to their utility:

\[\Pr[M(D) = r] \propto \exp\left(\frac{\varepsilon \cdot u(D, r)}{2\Delta u}\right)\]

where \emph{u(D, r)} is a utility function and \emph{Δu} is its
sensitivity.

\textbf{Privacy Accounting.} When multiple queries are issued, privacy
degrades according to composition theorems. We implement a privacy
accountant that tracks cumulative ε expenditure and enforces budget
limits.

\subsubsection{3.4.3 K-Anonymity and Rare Term
Filtering}\label{k-anonymity-and-rare-term-filtering}

K-anonymity requires that each record be indistinguishable from at least
\emph{k-1} other records with respect to quasi-identifying attributes
(Sweeney, 2002). In phenotype matching, rare HPO term combinations can
serve as quasi-identifiers that uniquely identify patients.

\textbf{Rare Term Filtering.} We mitigate quasi-identifier risk by
filtering phenotypes that appear infrequently in the reference corpus.
For a prevalence threshold \emph{τ} and corpus \emph{C}:

\[\Phi'(P) = \{t \in \Phi(P) : freq(t, C) \geq \tau\}\]

where \emph{freq(t, C)} is the number of patients in \emph{C} with term
\emph{t} or any of its descendants.

We implement two filtering strategies:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Suppression}: Remove rare terms entirely from the query
\item
  \textbf{Generalization}: Replace rare terms with their most specific
  ancestor having sufficient prevalence
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Result Suppression.} The k-anonymity guard suppresses query
results when fewer than \emph{k} patients match, preventing inference
about small cohorts:

\[R(Q) = \begin{cases} \text{top-}k \text{ results} & \text{if } |matches| \geq k \\ \varnothing & \text{otherwise} \end{cases}\]

\subsubsection{3.4.4 Composed Privacy
Pipeline}\label{composed-privacy-pipeline}

Our framework composes the three mechanisms in a configurable pipeline:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Rare Term Filtering} (pre-processing): Remove or generalize
  quasi-identifying phenotypes
\item
  \textbf{PSI Computation}: Securely compute phenotype overlap
\item
  \textbf{Similarity Scoring}: Calculate similarity metrics from PSI
  output
\item
  \textbf{DP Noise Addition}: Perturb similarity scores with calibrated
  noise
\item
  \textbf{K-Anonymity Check}: Suppress results below cohort size
  threshold
\end{enumerate}

Each mechanism can be independently enabled or disabled via
configuration. The privacy accountant tracks cumulative privacy loss
across all mechanisms.

\subsection{3.5 Evaluation Framework}\label{evaluation-framework}

\subsubsection{3.5.1 Retrieval Metrics}\label{retrieval-metrics}

We evaluate phenotype matching as an information retrieval task where,
for each query patient \emph{Q}, the system ranks all database patients
by similarity. Ground truth relevance is defined as patients sharing the
same underlying disease diagnosis.

\textbf{Precision at k (P@k).} The fraction of top-\emph{k} retrieved
patients that are relevant:

\[P@k = \frac{|\{P \in top_k : relevant(P)\}|}{k}\]

\textbf{Recall at k (R@k).} The fraction of all relevant patients
retrieved in the top-\emph{k}:

\[R@k = \frac{|\{P \in top_k : relevant(P)\}|}{|relevant|}\]

\textbf{Normalized Discounted Cumulative Gain (nDCG@k).} A ranking-aware
metric that rewards placing relevant results higher:

\[DCG@k = \sum_{i=1}^{k} \frac{rel_i}{\log_2(i+1)}\]

\[nDCG@k = \frac{DCG@k}{IDCG@k}\]

where \emph{IDCG@k} is the DCG of the ideal ranking.

\textbf{Mean Reciprocal Rank (MRR).} The average reciprocal position of
the first relevant result:

\[MRR = \frac{1}{|Q|}\sum_{q \in Q} \frac{1}{rank_q}\]

\subsubsection{3.5.2 Privacy Metrics}\label{privacy-metrics}

We quantify privacy protection through adversarial attack simulations.

\textbf{Membership Inference.} An adversary attempts to determine
whether a target patient is in the database based on query responses
(Shokri et al., 2017). We measure attack success rate as:

\[Adv_{MI} = Accuracy_{attack} - 0.5\]

where 0.5 represents random guessing.

\textbf{Attribute Inference.} An adversary attempts to infer undisclosed
phenotypes from partial query responses. We measure:

\[Adv_{AI} = \frac{TP + TN}{TP + TN + FP + FN} - Prior\]

where \emph{Prior} is the baseline accuracy from phenotype prevalence.

\subsubsection{3.5.3 Privacy-Utility
Frontier}\label{privacy-utility-frontier}

We characterize the privacy-utility tradeoff by sweeping privacy
parameters and plotting retrieval performance against privacy loss:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{DP Sweep}: ε ∈ \{0.1, 0.5, 1.0, 2.0, 5.0, 10.0, ∞\}
\item
  \textbf{K-Anonymity Sweep}: k ∈ \{2, 5, 10, 20, 50\}
\item
  \textbf{Rare Term Threshold}: τ ∈ \{0.001, 0.005, 0.01, 0.05\}
\end{itemize}

The Pareto frontier identifies optimal configurations that maximize
utility for a given privacy budget.

