\subsubsection{3.6.2 Synthetic Patient
Generation}\label{synthetic-patient-generation}

We generated synthetic patient cohorts by sampling from real disease
phenotype profiles. This approach produces realistic phenotype
distributions while avoiding the need for real patient data, which would
require institutional review board approval and data use agreements.

\textbf{Generation Procedure:}

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Disease Selection}: Sample \emph{d} diseases from HPOA,
  weighted by number of annotations
\item
  \textbf{Patient Assignment}: Assign \emph{n/d} patients to each
  disease (balanced design)
\item
  \textbf{Phenotype Sampling}: For each patient, sample phenotypes from
  the disease profile with recall rate \emph{ρ} (default: 0.75)
\item
  \textbf{Noise Addition}: Add \emph{η} fraction (default: 0.10) of
  random phenotypes from the corpus
\item
  \textbf{Ground Truth}: Patients with the same underlying disease are
  labeled as relevant
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Table 2: Evaluation Cohort Characteristics}

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}ll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Parameter & Value \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
Total patients & 500 \\
Diseases sampled & 100 \\
Patients per disease & 5 \\
Phenotype recall (ρ) & 0.75 \\
Noise rate (η) & 0.10 \\
Unique phenotypes & 1,145 \\
Mean phenotypes/patient & 10.4 ± 5.9 \\
Disease source distribution & 69\% OMIM, 31\% Orphanet \\
\end{longtable}
}

The resulting cohort exhibits phenotype distributions consistent with
real rare disease patients, with each patient having 3-24 observed
phenotypes (median: 9).

\subsection{3.7 Implementation}\label{implementation}

We implemented the privacy-preserving phenotype matching framework in
Python 3.10. The system comprises approximately 4,500 lines of code
organized into modular components.

\textbf{Core Dependencies:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{cryptography} (v41.0+): Elliptic curve operations for PSI
  (ECDH, HKDF)
\item
  \texttt{pronto} (v2.5+): HPO ontology parsing and traversal
\item
  \texttt{numpy} (v1.24+): Numerical computation and similarity matrices
\item
  \texttt{scipy} (v1.11+): Statistical distributions for DP mechanisms
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Standards Compliance:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  GA4GH Phenopackets v2.0: Native JSON schema support
\item
  GA4GH Beacon v2: Query/response adapters for federation
\item
  Matchmaker Exchange v1.1: Export compatibility for existing networks
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Computational Complexity:}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Similarity matrix computation: O(n²m) for \emph{n} patients with
  \emph{m} average phenotypes
\item
  PSI protocol: O(m) exponentiations per patient pair
\item
  DP noise addition: O(1) per score
\item
  Overall query processing: O(n · m) for ranking against \emph{n}
  database patients
\end{itemize}

The complete implementation, evaluation scripts, and synthetic datasets
are available at {[}repository URL{]} under an open-source license.

