\item
  \textbf{K-anonymity} prevents inference about small cohorts
\end{enumerate}

\subsubsection{4.4.5 Privacy-Utility Pareto
Frontier}\label{privacy-utility-pareto-frontier}

Figure 3 (not shown) plots the privacy-utility Pareto frontier,
identifying optimal configurations that maximize utility for a given
privacy level. Key operating points include:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{High utility, moderate privacy}: ε = 5.0, k = 5, 1\% filter →
  nDCG@10 = 0.962
\item
  \textbf{Balanced}: ε = 2.0, k = 5, 1\% filter → nDCG@10 = 0.928
\item
  \textbf{High privacy, reduced utility}: ε = 1.0, k = 5, 2\% filter →
  nDCG@10 = 0.851
\end{itemize}

\subsection{4.5 Computational
Performance}\label{computational-performance}

We measured computational overhead for the privacy-preserving pipeline
components.

\textbf{Table 13: Computational Overhead}

{\def\LTcaptype{none} % do not increment counter
\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Operation & Time (ms) & Notes \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
Similarity matrix (500×500) & 1,847 & All pairwise similarities \\
Per-patient similarity & 3.7 & Single query vs.~database \\
PSI per patient pair & 12.4 & EC operations, NIST P-256 \\
