These parameters achieve \textasciitilde93--97\% baseline utility while
providing meaningful protection. Institutions can adjust based on their
specific privacy requirements, regulatory constraints, and patient
population characteristics.

\subsubsection{5.3.2 Privacy Budget
Management}\label{privacy-budget-management}

For ongoing query systems, privacy budget management is essential. Each
query consumes a portion of the cumulative ε budget. We recommend:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Per-patient budgets}: Allocate a lifetime privacy budget
  (e.g., ε = 10) per patient, tracking consumption across queries.
\item
  \textbf{Query rate limiting}: Restrict query frequency to slow budget
  consumption and detect abuse.
\item
  \textbf{Budget renewal}: Consider periodic budget renewal (e.g.,
  annually) for patients with updated phenotypes.
\item
  \textbf{Opt-out mechanisms}: Allow patients to withdraw, invalidating
  future queries against their data.
\end{enumerate}

Our implementation includes a privacy accountant that tracks cumulative
ε expenditure and can enforce budget limits.

\subsubsection{5.3.3 Integration Pathways}\label{integration-pathways}

We envision three deployment models:

\textbf{Institutional deployment.} A single institution deploys the
system for internal matching. Privacy mechanisms protect against insider
threats and audit compliance. This model requires minimal infrastructure
change.

\textbf{Federated deployment.} Multiple institutions participate via
MME-compatible interfaces. Each institution runs a privacy-preserving
node that responds to queries without revealing raw phenotypes. This
model requires coordinated deployment but enables cross-institutional
matching.

\textbf{Centralized trusted service.} A trusted third party operates the
matching service, with institutions submitting encrypted phenotypes.
This model simplifies deployment but requires trust in the central
operator.

Each model involves different trust assumptions and architectural
requirements. Our modular design supports all three.

\subsubsection{5.3.4 Regulatory Alignment}\label{regulatory-alignment}

Privacy-preserving phenotype matching aligns with key regulatory
frameworks:

\textbf{HIPAA.} The Privacy Rule permits de-identified data sharing. Our
k-anonymity and rare term filtering support de-identification
requirements. DP provides additional protection exceeding minimum
standards.

\textbf{GDPR.} The right to data protection is balanced against research
exemptions. Privacy-preserving computation demonstrates ``privacy by
design'' and ``data minimization'' principles. Consent frameworks should
disclose matching participation and privacy mechanisms.

\textbf{Common Rule.} For federally funded research in the US, IRB
approval is required for human subjects research. Privacy-preserving
matching may qualify for expedited review when risks are minimal, though
IRB practices vary.

We recommend institutional consultation with compliance officers, as
specific requirements depend on data sources, patient populations, and
use cases.

\subsection{5.4 Limitations}\label{limitations}

\subsubsection{5.4.1 Evaluation
Limitations}\label{evaluation-limitations}

Our evaluation has several limitations that contextualize the results:

\textbf{Synthetic patients.} We evaluated on synthetic patients
generated from real disease profiles rather than actual patient records.
While this approach produces realistic phenotype distributions and
enables reproducible evaluation, it may not capture all complexities of
clinical phenotyping---including phenotype evolution over time,
phenotypic heterogeneity within diseases, and annotation inconsistencies
across institutions.

\textbf{Balanced cohort design.} Our cohort assigns exactly 5 patients
per disease, creating uniform ground truth. Real databases have skewed
disease distributions, with common conditions overrepresented and rare
diseases potentially having single patients. Performance on extremely
rare diseases (n=1 patients) cannot be assessed in our balanced design.

\textbf{Single-institution simulation.} We simulated queries within a
single cohort rather than across federated institutions with
heterogeneous annotation practices. Cross-institutional matching may
face additional challenges from differing phenotyping conventions, HPO
version mismatches, and variable annotation depth.

\textbf{Limited privacy attack evaluation.} While we measured membership
and attribute inference resistance, more sophisticated attacks (e.g.,
model inversion, query-based reconstruction) merit further
investigation. Adversarial capabilities evolve, and ongoing security
assessment is essential.

\subsubsection{5.4.2 Technical Limitations}\label{technical-limitations}

\textbf{Semi-honest adversary model.} Our PSI implementation assumes
semi-honest (honest-but-curious) adversaries who follow the protocol but
attempt to learn from observations. Malicious adversaries who deviate
from the protocol are not addressed. Malicious-secure PSI protocols
exist but incur substantial overhead.

\textbf{Computational overhead.} PSI adds \textasciitilde12ms per
patient pair, making real-time queries against large databases
challenging. For a database of 100,000 patients, naive PSI would require
\textasciitilde20 minutes per query. Approximate methods and indexing
could reduce this but merit separate evaluation.

\textbf{Phenotype-only matching.} We focus on phenotype matching without
genomic data. Clinical matching often integrates both modalities.
Extending privacy protection to combined phenotype-genotype matching
requires additional mechanisms.

\subsubsection{5.4.3 Scope Limitations}\label{scope-limitations}

\textbf{Clinical validation.} We have not validated clinical utility
with actual rare disease diagnoses. Whether privacy-preserving matching
leads to diagnoses that would not otherwise occur requires prospective
clinical studies.

\textbf{User interface.} Our implementation provides programmatic APIs
but not clinician-facing interfaces. Effective deployment requires UX
design for clinical workflows.

\textbf{Longitudinal phenotyping.} Phenotypes evolve as patients age and
diseases progress. Our static matching does not address temporal
phenotype dynamics.

\subsection{5.5 Ethical Considerations}\label{ethical-considerations}

\subsubsection{5.5.1 Balancing Research and
Privacy}\label{balancing-research-and-privacy}

Privacy-preserving phenotype matching navigates a fundamental tension:
rare disease research benefits from data sharing, but patients have
legitimate privacy interests. Our approach attempts to maximize research
utility while providing meaningful protection, but tradeoffs remain.

Strong privacy protection (low ε) reduces the information available to
researchers, potentially slowing discovery. Weak protection (high ε) may
expose patients to identification risks. There is no universally correct
balance---appropriate parameters depend on disease sensitivity, patient
preferences, and research context.

We advocate for transparent communication with patients about privacy
mechanisms and their limitations. Informed consent should explain that
privacy-preserving computation reduces but does not eliminate
identification risk, and that residual risk depends on adversary
capabilities that may evolve.

\subsubsection{5.5.2 Equity Considerations}\label{equity-considerations}

Privacy-preserving systems could exacerbate or ameliorate health equity
disparities:

\textbf{Potential benefits.} Privacy protection may enable participation
by institutions serving underrepresented populations who are
particularly sensitive to data sharing. Broader participation improves
research diversity.

\textbf{Potential risks.} Complex privacy mechanisms may be deployed
primarily at well-resourced institutions, creating a two-tier system.
Computational overhead may disadvantage institutions with limited
infrastructure.

\textbf{Mitigation.} Open-source implementation, clear documentation,
and cloud deployment options can lower adoption barriers. International
collaboration should consider resource disparities across settings.

\subsubsection{5.5.3 Secondary Use
Limitations}\label{secondary-use-limitations}

Our framework is designed for patient matching, not broader surveillance
or commercial profiling. Technical controls (query rate limiting, audit
logging) and governance policies should prevent misuse. Terms of service
for federated networks should prohibit secondary uses inconsistent with
research purposes.

\subsubsection{5.5.4 Patient Agency}\label{patient-agency}

Patients should retain agency over their participation in matching
systems:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Informed consent}: Clear explanation of matching purpose,
  privacy mechanisms, and residual risks
\item
  \textbf{Opt-out rights}: Ability to withdraw at any time, with
  matching against their data disabled
\item
  \textbf{Result notification}: Option to be informed when their data
  contributes to a match
\item
  \textbf{Benefit sharing}: Consideration of how patients benefit from
  discoveries enabled by their data
\end{itemize}

These principles align with emerging frameworks for patient-centered
genomics research (Ramoni et al., 2017) and should guide deployment
policies.

\subsection{5.6 Summary}\label{summary}

Our evaluation demonstrates that privacy-preserving phenotype matching
is technically feasible with acceptable utility costs. Phenotype
similarity effectively identifies disease-sharing patients, IC-weighted
metrics provide optimal performance, and layered privacy mechanisms
offer configurable protection. Key findings include:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Baseline retrieval is highly effective} (nDCG@10
  \textgreater{} 99\%), validating phenotype-based matching
\item
  \textbf{Privacy mechanisms impose modest costs} (3.5--7\% utility loss
  for practical configurations)
\item
  \textbf{Mechanism composition provides defense in depth} against
  complementary threat vectors
\item
  \textbf{Practical deployment is achievable} with appropriate parameter
  selection and governance
\end{enumerate}

Limitations include reliance on synthetic evaluation data, semi-honest
security assumptions, and absence of clinical validation. Ethical
deployment requires transparent communication, patient agency, and
ongoing attention to equity implications.

The path forward involves validation on real patient cohorts, extension
to multi-omic data, and integration with existing rare disease
infrastructure. Privacy-preserving computation offers a promising
approach to the perennial challenge of enabling research collaboration
while protecting patient confidentiality.

